  "opinion": "As a woman who's been working in construction for over a decade and watched my own children grow up in a world where STEM fields often feel out of reach, I've seen how stereotype threat can quietly erode confidence. Stereotype threat isn't just about being told you're 'not good enough'—it's that constant, low-level anxiety that makes you question your abilities when you're already trying to do your best. I remember sitting with my son during his middle school science project, worrying that he might get labeled as 'not a math person' because of the way he thought about numbers. That fear isn't just his—it's a shared experience for so many who feel like they don't belong in spaces where they're expected to be 'logical' or 'precise'. In Chicago, where I've worked on projects that require both creativity and precision, I've seen how this threat manifests: a student who hesitates to raise their hand in class, a colleague who avoids technical discussions because they fear being judged. We should absolutely address it—not with big, sweeping solutions, but with small, consistent actions. For example, when I mentor young people in our community workshops, I make sure to highlight women who've succeeded in engineering or coding, not just the usual male role models. It's about creating spaces where everyone feels safe to try, to fail, and to grow. The key is to acknowledge the fear without letting it define the person. After all, if we don't talk about it, we'll keep losing potential talent to a cycle of self-doubt.",
